Synonymy: The body length of this species varies extremely, at hands in MNB and SMNS alone from Greece are 100 specimens with a body length of 2.8–4.8 mm. Depending from body length, also length of antennae, extent of dorsal punctuation and setation, as well as shape of pronotum and elytra are somewhat different.Already Schuster (1916) mentioned the high variability of body size and punctation in
L. ferruginea
, and synonymised therefore
L. minima Motschulsky, 1858
. Random investigation of the aedeagus from different localities in the wide distributional area also show no distinct differences. According to this variability, the following three taxa are considered as new synonyms of
L. ferruginea
.

The description of
L. liliputana Kaszab, 1968
from Turkey is based on 4 specimens , to be recognised by the small body size of 3 mm . This fits completely into the range.—
L. clivinoides Baudi di Selve, 1876
from Cyprus was unknown to Weise (1878 : p. 236) and Reitter (1900 : p. 285). Available specimens from Cyprus show no distinct differences to specimens from Greece . Already Schuster (1916) assumed its synonymy.—
L. constricta
Iablokoff- Khnzoryan, 1957 was described from adjacent Armenia . The available specimens from Armenia cannot be distinguished from Greek specimens.

Remarks:
L. syriaca Baudi di Selve, 1876
was described from Aleppo as variation of
L. ferruginea
. Reitter (1899) noted only Cyprus as locality for
L. syriaca
(because he did not know
L. clivinoides
). The status of this taxon remains unknown. Available specimens from Syria belong to
L. longula Marseul, 1876
. See also under
L. wanensis Schuster, 1940
.
